Annie: Well, I think we've cleared all of that up now!

Understanding Types
-------------------

Lin: Yes, I think we're getting a lot closer to helping your roommate out,
Annie, but can you text her to see what she and the parents have
been doing recently to try to get the kid to go to bed?

JJ: Good idea. We know it was sometimes "do nothing," but maybe not every time.

Annie: Sure, I'll text her now and let you know what she says.

// Note: This shows screenshot of messages between Annie's roommate and parents
::messages_image [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar2 label="Texts from the babysitter"]

Annie: She texted right back. See for yourselves.

Lin: So what is this? Punishment or reinforcement?

JJ: You'd think yelling was punishment! But it doesn't seem to have worked as punishment,
because his refusing to go to sleep got worse. So in this case, yelling was a reinforcer.
If yelling worked as a punisher, we would expect that he would stop the problem behaviors
after being yelled at.

Annie: In other words, their attempt to control his behavior gave him something he wanted, probably attention,
so every time they tried to bring the problem under control, they were only making it worse.

Lin: That means we need to figure out things to suggest that will reinforce cooperation. We don't want to accidentally reinforce the wrong thing!

Annie: Hey guys, there's still something we need to get clear in our own heads before we offer any solutions to my roommate. The most effective behavior modification technique, according to what we learned earlier, is **positive**  reinforcement. But I'm not really clear yet on the difference between positive and negative reinforcement.

::operant_conditioning_reinforcement_notes [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar2 label="Notes: positive vs. negative reinforcement"]

JJ: I just checked back through my notes ... here's what I have.

JJ: So, positive doesn't mean good, and negative doesn't mean bad. Instead, positive means adding something, and negative means taking something away! And it's the same for punishment.

::operant_conditioning_reinforcement_notes2 [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar2 label="Notes: positive vs. negative punishment"]

JJ: Look! Here's what I have in my notes.

Lin: So positive punishment would be like spanking the child every time he tries to avoid bedtime. The adult is **adding** spanking, something that is **undesirable**, to **decrease** the child's behavior of avoiding bedtime.

Annie: And negative punishment would be like taking away his favorite toy whenever he avoids bedtime. The adult is **taking away** the toy, something **desirable**, to decrease the child's behavior of avoiding bedtime.

::operant_conditioning_poster [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar2 label="Reinforcement & punishment chart"]

JJ: I found this chart on the Internet. I think it sums things up nicely!

Lin: I'm still not as clear on this as I would like to be. Maybe some practice would help!

JJ: Maybe we can take some of the things that the parents have already tried or that we suggested early on and figure out what category they fit into? I don't know about you, but that would help me.

::conditioning_example_chart [display=target:psych_sba_sidebar2 label="Categorize the examples"]

Annie: OK, let's give it a try!

